cational Medium -- t“Practically I Am a Fundamentalist” : Twentieth Century orthodox Jews Contend With Evolution and Its Implications -- tSection III. Contemporary American Judaism -- tAmerican Jewish Views of Evolution and Intelligent Design -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDivided into three sections, this work explains how the concepts and practices of traditional European Judaism were adapted to North American culture beginning in the late nineteenth century. Part I focuses on the ideas and activities of Cyrus Adler (1863-1940), one of the most prominent leaders of the traditionalist United States Jewish community in his era. The issues in these essays include the origins of American Jewish history as a field of study, the Kehilla experiments of the early twentieth century, and the relationship between the Jewish Theological Seminary and Orthodox Judaism. Part II deals with the beginnings of Hasidic Judaism in North America prior to the Second World War. It also includes several studies investigating the shaping of the worldview of Orthodox Judaism in contemporary North America. Part III examines the issue of contemporary American Jewish attitudes toward evolution and intelligent design.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aJewish religious educationzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewish religious educationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszUnited StatesxPolitics and governmenty19th century. 0aJewszUnited StatesxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aJudaismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aJudaismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aJacobson, Maxine, eco